      <span class="pf-section-label">FORMBY LOCAL KNOWLEDGE</span>
      <h2 style="text-align:center;">The Most Common Formby Radiator Mistake. And Why It Keeps Happening.</h2>
      <p class="pf-sub">Formby has some of the largest rooms, highest ceilings and most generous bay windows in Merseyside. These rooms need correctly sized radiators. The most common Formby radiator job we attend is a room that has always been cold despite the heating being on, and the cause is almost always an undersized radiator that was fitted without a BTU calculation.</p>

      <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr;gap:1.5rem;margin-top:2rem;">

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-orange">
          <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Why Formby Rooms Are So Commonly Undersized</strong>
          <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">A Formby 4-bed detached has larger rooms than the Merseyside average. A sitting room with a bay window in Freshfield or Formby Village might have a floor area of 20 to 25 square metres with high ceilings. The correct radiator for this room might have a BTU output of 8,000 to 10,000 BTU. A standard double panel 600mm x 1400mm radiator delivers around 4,500 to 5,500 BTU. Fitting a standard radiator in a large Formby room is correct for an average-sized room, it is significantly wrong for a large period room with a bay window and high ceilings. The room will never reach the set temperature regardless of how long the heating runs. We calculate the exact BTU requirement for every Formby room before recommending a radiator size. No recommendation is made based on what fits the wall or what was there before.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-orange">
          <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Column Radiators in Formby Bay Windows. The Right Solution for Period Rooms.</strong>
          <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">A bay window in a Freshfield or Formby Village period property is a beautiful feature and a significant source of cold air ingress. A correctly sized radiator positioned directly in the bay recess pushes warm air upward against the cold glass and creates a thermal barrier that heats the room efficiently. A standard double panel radiator on a side wall in the same room is less effective because it does not counteract the cold from the bay directly. For period Formby rooms with high ceilings and bay windows, a taller column radiator in the bay recess delivers the correct heat output, counteracts the window cold effectively and looks correct in the period setting. We advise on this at the quote visit for every Formby period room. The column style, height and width are specified for the room's actual BTU requirement, not chosen for appearance alone.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-orange">
          <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Adding Radiators to Formby Extensions</strong>
          <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Many Formby homeowners extend their properties with kitchen extensions, utility rooms or rear reception rooms. If the extension does not have underfloor heating and needs a radiator connected to the existing central heating circuit, we assess the pipe route, the existing system boiler capacity and the correct BTU requirement for the new room at the quote visit. For Formby multi-zone systems, we also confirm which zone the new radiator should connect to and how the zone valve and thermostat should be set to include the new room correctly. Adding a radiator to a Formby multi-zone system without checking the zone configuration is a common mistake that leaves the new room either always on or always cold depending on which zone valve position it connects to.</p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>


