  <!-- SIGNS -->
  <section class="pf-section" style="background:#f8fafc;">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 style="text-align:center;">Signs Your Formby Radiators Need Attention</h2>
      <p class="pf-sub">These are the most common radiator problems we attend in Formby and Freshfield properties.</p>
      <div class="pf-signs" style="margin-top:2rem;">
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>A large Formby room that is always cold despite the heating being on</strong><p>The most common Formby radiator problem. The room has an undersized radiator that cannot heat the space correctly. We calculate the correct BTU for the room and supply a radiator that matches. Two previous companies doing like-for-like replacements will not fix this, the correct size must be specified.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Bay window sitting room cold even in the corner by the window</strong><p>A radiator on a side wall in a bay window room is less effective than a correctly sized radiator directly under the bay. The bay position counteracts cold air from the window more efficiently. We advise on position as well as size at the quote visit.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Extension room with no radiator</strong><p>A Formby kitchen or rear reception room extension without a radiator, or with only a small designer radiator that cannot heat the new open plan space. Adding a correctly sized radiator to the existing circuit and confirming zone assignment for a multi-zone system.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>One zone in a multi-zone system heating noticeably less well than another</strong><p>If one zone of your Formby system consistently underperforms, individual radiators in that zone may be cold at the bottom due to sludge, or the zone may have an incorrectly balanced radiator circuit. We diagnose the cause at the quote visit.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Radiator cold at the bottom</strong><p>Sludge and magnetite build-up. Bleeding does not fix this. A power flush of the system is the correct treatment. In a larger Formby system with multiple radiators affected, a full power flush before any new radiators are fitted prevents the new ones being contaminated immediately.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Radiator visibly corroded or leaking</strong><p>Surface rust on an older Formby radiator should be replaced. A corroding radiator releases iron oxide into the system and accelerates sludge build-up across the whole circuit, including into a newer and more expensive Worcester Bosch or Vaillant boiler.</p></div></div>
      </div>
